15704492.review:
I've always been a fan of tycoon games, ever since I was little, so when given the opportunity to review Software Inc., I didn't even think twice. And after a "few" hours of playing it, I don't have to think twice before recommending it to any fan of the genre, and even to those that aren't so familiar with it.

[i]Computers themselves, and software yet to be developed, will revolutionize the way we learn.


Steve Jobs[/i]

Without any further delay, I present to you my review of Software Inc..

[h1]Gameplay[/h1]
Let he who has never thought about developing some sort of software throw the first byte and I shall compute it.
Software Inc. is a game that allows you, the player, to develop your own software, while competing against AI companies that can easily go bankrupt, or simply bought out (I'm looking at you Microsoft!). From choosing your company's name, to the year you wish you start, you'll have a wide range of options to customise your character, and surely even more in the future. You won't be able to start a gigantic company from the get-go, so you'll have to work hard and complete some side contracts while developing your company's first software. And after developing that first piece, you'll just find out that the critics tagged it as crapware.
Once you get the hang of it, you'll find out it's incredibly fun to develop your IPs, whether you choose to develop an AntiVirus IP, a Games IP, or even an Operating System IP, and just when you're about to release that latest piece of technology, your thoughts will be: "Ok, just one more and I'll go to bed." Trust me, it won't be just one more.
Sure, the game isn't perfect. Even simple changes could make the game more enjoyable. But that's why it's Early Access, and that's why the developers are so active around the forums. Software Inc. is a true gem.

[h1]Pros[/h1]
[list][*] Extremely active development team, not only around the forums, but also providing some hotfixes;
[*] Delightful graphics that despite not being a vital part for the genre, is always a plus;
[*] Plenty of tutorials, pretty much one for each function, and they're all truly insightful;
[*] Many options and improvements for each type of software;
[*] Minimalist UI, containing everything the player will need;
[*] A good amount of customization available to create the player's character, from colors to skills;
[*] Enjoyable environment and sound effects.[/list]

Considering it's an Early Access (EA) game, I've decided to add a "Neutral" category, for details I consider important, but not gamebreakers, and could easily improve the gameplay if attended.

[h1]Neutral[/h1]
[list][*] Despite being pretty good, the 'Build Mode' needs some improvement, especially to allow the player to build L and T shaped corridors, [strike]as well as to have a "bulk" buy option[/strike], or even a copy/paste, since it can be pretty boring after a while to do the plan/buy the same things over and over again;
[*] It feels like the staff loses too much time eating/drinking/going to the bathroom during the day, even if all those things are two steps away;
[*] Could use some more objects, but I'm sure these will be added in the future;
[*] Couple minor bugs, not gamebreaking, but could improve the game's quality if fixed.[/list]

Considering most of the "Cons" I had in mind were already mentioned by the developers as something they're planning to fix, this list will be somewhat short, and I'm sure it will be even shorter after a while. I will, however, still list some that I feel are in bad shape, despite being mentioned by the developers.

[h1]Cons[/h1]
[list][*] In dire need of some balancing overall, mostly around the profits, stocks market and reputation;
[*] Staff are not only extremely demanding, but also incredibly well paid;
[*] Needs a new/better notification system to alert the player of new technology and/or rival's releases.[/list]

[h1]Verdict[/h1]
I'd give it a [b]8/10[/b], which could easily increase to a 9, and even a 10, with further updates and some more balancing. I've no doubt that, if attended to, it will be one of the best, if not the best, of the genre.
